        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuilding\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"James, this first phase is all about reintroducing running load gently and earning trust back from your right foot. Every run stays within your physio-cleared window of 20 minutes max at easy effort — that means the slower end of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone, roughly 5:45–6:12 per km. Walking breaks are built in by default: run 3–4 minutes, walk 1 minute, repeat. If your foot gives you any signal during a run, the walk break becomes your best friend — use it without hesitation. Three days per week only (e.g., Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday), with Saturday as your longer effort. Cross-training on off-days (swimming, cycling) is welcome if your physio approves, and it helps maintain aerobic fitness without foot load. Weekly distance builds from ~8 km to ~12 km, staying well within the 10% weekly progression rule. A deload week at week 4 drops volume back ~20% before the next phase begins.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":12,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"notes\":\"If your physio gives the green light after phase one, this phase begins to extend your Saturday long run slightly beyond 20 minutes — but only with clearance. Until then, all three sessions remain capped at 20 minutes. The focus shifts from 'surviving the run' to 'feeling comfortable on the run.' You might notice the walk breaks becoming less necessary — that's a great sign, but keep them available on any day your foot feels different. Easy pace can nudge toward the middle of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone (around 5:45–5:50 per km) as your foot tolerates load better. Weekly distance builds from ~12 km to ~18 km over four weeks, with a deload at week 8. No speed work, no tempo, no intervals — your physio will tell you when that door opens, and we'll be ready when it does.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":22,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85/15 easy/moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":349,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":349,\"notes\":\"This phase is about consolidating the fitness you've rebuilt — not pushing into new territory yet. Three weeks of steady, confident running at easy effort, with your Saturday long run as the centerpiece each week. By this point you should be running continuously and comfortably, with walk breaks used only by choice rather than necessity. Weekly distance sits between 18–22 km, which for three days per week gives you roughly 6–8 km per session. The pace can settle naturally toward the upper end of your Daniels-Gilbert easy zone (5:25–5:45 per km) if that feels right — but never forced. This phase has no deload built in because it follows a deload at the end of phase two, but listen carefully to your foot. Any returning discomfort is a signal to revisit the previous phase's approach.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":14,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":14,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy/recovery\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"The final week is a deliberate, intentional step back — not because anything went wrong, but because recovery is where the adaptation actually happens. Think of this week as banking the fitness gains from the previous 11 weeks. Two easy runs of 20–25 minutes and one optional cross-training session. Pace is relaxed, effort is low, and the goal is to arrive at week 13 feeling fresh, confident, and ready for whatever comes next — whether that's a return to structured training, a conversation with your physio about speed work, or setting your sights back on that 10K PR.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James's plan is built around three non-negotiable realities: active plantar fasciitis, a physio clearance limited to 20-minute easy runs, and a pre-injury pace-zone index of 46.5 that tells us his aerobic engine is solid — it just needs a safe runway to come back online. The 12-week structure uses four phases (Base → Build → Peak → Recovery) that progressively restore running volume at 3 days per week while keeping intensity exclusively in the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone throughout. Speed work, threshold runs, and intervals are intentionally absent from this entire plan — not because James isn't capable of them, but because the plantar fascia needs consistent, low-load stimulus to remodel and strengthen, and introducing intensity too early is the most common reason runners end up back at square one. Walk breaks are prescribed in phase one and remain available throughout as a tool, not a sign of failure. The 10% weekly volume progression rule is respected in every phase, and deload weeks at weeks 4 and 8 give the foot and the whole system a chance to absorb the accumulated load before building again. Paces are anchored to James's Daniels-Gilbert easy zone (5:25–6:12 per km), with the early phases favoring the slower end of that range and later phases allowing a natural drift toward the faster end as comfort improves.\",\"warnings\":\"Important prerequisites and safety notes for James: (1) This plan operates entirely within your current physio clearance — 20-minute easy runs only, no speed work. Before progressing beyond 20 minutes in Phase 2, you must obtain explicit clearance from your physiotherapist. (2) Walking breaks are not optional in Phase 1 — they are part of the prescription. If you experience any foot pain during a run, take a walking break immediately. If pain persists after walking, end the session and consult your physio. (3) Plantar fasciitis can flare without much warning. A day that feels fine in the morning can feel very different after 15 minutes of running. Trust the signals your foot sends — they are data, not weakness. (4) This plan does not include any speed work, tempo, intervals, or repetitions. These will be introduced in a subsequent plan once your physio confirms full clearance. (5) If you experience sharp heel pain, significant swelling, or pain that alters your gait at any point, stop running and contact your physiotherapist before your next scheduled session. (6) Cross-training (pool running, cycling, swimming) is a genuine option throughout this plan and can help maintain aerobic fitness on non-running days — check with your physio on what they'd recommend given your foot.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
